MK5 skeinforge instructions:
If itâ€™s printing way blobby, try lowering w/t (in all places in skeinforge - carve and fill I think). Or increasing feed speed.
If itâ€™s printing with gaps in-between lines increase w/t or decrease feed speed. There are some key skeinforge values that I think are very important with a cupcake MK5. Hereâ€™s some of the key values that I use. (Iâ€™ve also included my skeinforge profile)

  • Layer height .38
  • Perimeter w/t 1.6
    • Fill:
  • w/t 1.7
  • Thread sequence - perimeter, loops, infill

  • j/w 100

    M6 T0 (Wait for tool to heat up)

    • Stretch: (activate it! pretty machine dependent I think but I changed the following. This scad script generates any layercake you want for multiple extruders to allow quick and easy calibration of offsets.

It's much easier to calibrate the nozzle offsets when you are sure the layers are just supposed to stack neatly. I recommend printing it without top and bottom, and preferably a few perimiters.
Use eeprom offsets so you can change them on the go. This can be done from Repetier by selecting the eeprom menu but probably from other tools as well. Let it run a few layers, then adjust and watch. A single print was used to get the two first hotends in my setup (a tripple) aligned and even then it didn't take all layers.
You know you are spot on when the object looks same from all sides. No dominant color on any side. You can generate triple setups with this head too, it's all in variables for easy modifications.

title: Dropping Eggs from Drones for Fun and Science - Rotating Egg Drop Mechanism
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text: I was invited by a local school to participate in their Egg-Drop science event and this is one of the results. The reason they invited me was because they wanted to do something different this year. Instead of dropping boxes to protect contained eggs they wanted to drop eggs from a drone or multirotor and try to catch and protect the eggs. This was the second version of our dropping device. (Check out the first one here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:855304) This version uses paper cups, 6mm threaded rod, 4mm nuts and bolts, and a continuous rotation servo motor. More information at Instructables.com (http://www.instructables.com/id/Dropping-eggs-from-drones-for-fun-and-science/)

I printed all of the parts with PLA, two perimeters, 15% infill, 2 solid layers top and bottom. I wanted it to be as light as possible.   
I mounted the servo to the top carriage first.  Then I measured and cut the threaded rod so that the mounting bracket held the cups below the body of the drone but off of the ground.  Next I mounted the custom servo arm on the motor. I used 3 nuts as spacers between the top carriage and the bottom carriage and one more nut with a lock washer to hold the bottom carriage in place.  A little locktight kept everything nice and rigid.

I had two things: A broken penknife on my desk, and a need to showcase the new Silver PLA at http://diamondage.co.nz/pla.html - preferably with something shiny. Like that knife blade. Ahah! I now have a light handle that fills my hand well and has a nice lanyard hole too. This handle is configured to accept a 2.5mm x 25mm x79mm blade with a 6mm pivot hole. The OpenSCAD file is parametric though, so you can fiddle around to suit whatever blade you happen to have at hand or knock up in the forge.

Make sure the plastic that your printer puts out is up to the job. In particular, don't skimp on plastic around the pivot or you'll give yourself a nasty injury.
Secure the blade with an M6 washer on one side, thin M6 press nut on the other, and low-profile M6 bolt to act as the pivot. There is no spring or lock.

I bought this dual relay board to control a CNC spindle using Grbl, and I needed a bumper for it, so I designed this simple thing. OpenSCAD source is included so the thing can be further remixed. License is GPLV3. Update 07/06/15
Externally identical, added two small reinforcements for each column.
Requires 4 x small and short self-threading screws to hold the relay board and 2 x wood screws to mount onto any wood surface.
I took inspiration from http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:65997, but wanted something with the option of putting the rod on 608 bearings, so I created this.

You can use this with or without bearings. Minimally, you will need two printed towers and a ~8mm rod. The regular rectangular tower is easier to print vertically, but will restrict the range on the z-axis on the power-cable side of the printer due to the extruder motor, so I created a tapered version as well. There are small endcaps included that work (tightly) with a 5/16 threaded rod and keep it from coming off the towers. Use these or something similar to keep the rod from sliding out. If you use bearings, just slide them on and rest them in place in the top center of the towers. If you don't use bearings, just set the rod into the V-slots. No tools necessary for spool changes either way - just carefully lift the rod from the tower and make the switch. Additionally, my printrbot+'s (v2) wrapped cabling kept getting caught on one of the thumbscrews for the bed leveler when the platform moved in the Y direction, so the towers each have a 45 degree 8mm square hole to hold accessories, and I included an optional simple hook that I used to suspend the cables via rubberbands above the print bed. This should work for anything with exposed 12mm Z rods like the printrbot+, but I've only tried it with mine. Update Added another 'accessory': a Maglite clip for 18mm flashlights. Slice with supports for printing. It's not perfect since the extruder and fan assembly casts a shadow, but it helps out. Make sure your towers are on the Z rods far enough to be secure.

title: Parametric Tyre for OpenRC Truggy Wheel

description.text:
Being a big fan of RC cars, OpenSCAD and NinjaFlex I decided to develop this parametric RC car tyre. With the default parameters it fits the Daniel Noree (barspin) 3D printed OpenRC Truggy wheel, but I also tweaked it to fit a number of different sized wheels, including a 3D printed Kyosho Mini Z wheels I also designed. For more information on it's development visit:
http://3DPrintHQ.com/bespoke-3d-printed-rc-car-tyres-designed-openscad

This parametric OpenRC Truggy tyre was designed and 3D printed by myself. The one you can see in the picture fitted to Daniel Norees OpenRC Truggy wheel was printed using the following: Material: Black NinjaFlex
Infill: 5%
Shells: 8
Layer: 0.3 mm
Temp: 235 degrees
Speed: 30 mm/s I experimented with a number of settings but when using these it printed really well and seems quite rugged too. Due to the fact that you need to print slowly with NinjaFlex it took about 8 hours to print one tyre. The dimensions were perfect for the Truggy wheel but as NinjaFlex doesn't stretch much I had to use washing up liquid to help it onto the wheel rim. A final dip into warm water (about 50 degrees) helped soften the tyre and complete the fitting. Feel free to experiment with this tyre and if it proves popular I plan to make ongoing improvements based on your feedback.

description.text:
This is a combination of two ideas: Filament Storage Solution (wstein)
Filament Quick Change Roller (Tony_D) I liked wstein's Ikea box storage solution but the roller wheel system makes it much easier to change one of the spools. Still not perfect: the rolls tend to "derail" sometimes, especially when the box is not filled completely. I have ordered some 608ZZ ball-bearings online and plan to use 4 of these and two pieces of PVC tube, instead of the small roller wheels. That way, all the spools will roll together, but probably smoother. If it works, I'll post an update!

BOM:
  • 1 Ikea Samla 22l box with lid
  • 2 metal rods, diameter 8 mm, length 299 mm
  • 2 3D-printed support parts
  • 16 3D-printed roller wheels (4 wheels per filament spool)
    • Parts can be printed in PLA or ABS, no support needed. No drilling required. Just need a metal saw for the rods (I used a solid iron rod, 2m long, was 6 euros and enough for 3 boxes).

here's a DIY method of making cheap, flexible dome connectors! when i saw WilliamAAdams' simple tetrahedron http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:8306 it reminded me of the tubing connectors i saw in the great domebook 2 http://www.scribd.com/doc/37419493/Domebook-2 the advantage of a flexible connector is that it doesn't require absolute precision in strut lengths. this makes for easier domeraising and allows the structure to equalize gracefully. for a similar approach not involving nuts and bolts, see: http://simplydifferently.org/Geodesic_Dome_Notes?page=17

you'll need some vinyl tubing and some nuts, bolts, and washers in addition to dowels or poles cut to the appropriate lengths. these instructions are adapted from WilliamAAdams' excellent documentation. 1) decide on the type of struts you'll be using. we used 3/8" dowels because we had a lot of scrap laying around.
2) get a large quantity of tubing that will snugly fit over the ends of the struts. the dome pictured here required almost 20 feet of tubing.
3) cut the tubing into 2-3" long lengths.
4) drill a hole in the center of each piece of tubing.
5) thread a washer and three lengths of tubing on a bolt, then cap it with another washer and a nut. spread the tubing lengths out to form a hexagonal shape, then tighten the whole assembly.
6) assemble your dome or sphere by sliding the struts into the tubing. whenever a pentagon is needed, simply leave one of the tubes empty. a 2V icosahedron will require 26 connectors. checkout http://desertdomes.com or http://simplydifferently.org for dome assembly diagrams and strut calculators.

description.text: I am not an artist - the model was created by Adrien Liotard! Someone had requested a parted-out Tachikoma model - here it is. I rescaled and rotated the individual parts to better facilitate printing. single.stl.gz is a single pre-assembled Tachikoma model. It is gzipped because of its size (~56MB uncompressed). single-plate.stl is a custom arrangement of the parts needed to build a single Tachikoma. The other stl files are the individual parts used to create single*.stl. There are also gzipped AMF files for each of the plating layouts.

The single model will need some small supports around the cabin and under the bot. The single-plate model will likely need supports for the legs, but should be support-free otherwise. If your slicer wants to put support material inside the cups of the leg cups, just pop them out after printing.
